23. RACE CONDITION
============================================================

Race condition tab hoti hai jab multiple threads shared mutable data ko concurrently access/modify karte hain aur result execution timing/order par depend karne lagta hai.


Example:

count++;


Ye logically ek line hai, lekin conceptually multiple steps involve karta hai:

1. count read karo
2. increment karo
3. value write karo


Example:

count = 5


Thread 1 reads:

5


Thread 2 reads:

5


Thread 1 writes:

6


Thread 2 writes:

6


Expected:

7


Actual:

6


Isko Lost Update problem kaha ja sakta hai.


============================================================
24. RACE CONDITION EXAMPLE
============================================================

class Counter {

    int count = 0;

    public void increment() {

        count++;
    }
}


Main:

Counter counter = new Counter();


Thread t1 = new Thread(() -> {

    for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {

        counter.increment();
    }

});


Thread t2 = new Thread(() -> {

    for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {

        counter.increment();
    }

});


t1.start();
t2.start();

t1.join();
t2.join();


System.out.println(counter.count);


Expected:

20000


Possible Actual:

19872
19940
etc.


Result run-to-run change ho sakta hai.


