                    System.out.println(
                            "Running"
                    );

                });


thread.join();


============================================================
54. VIRTUAL THREAD PER TASK EXECUTOR
============================================================

Java 21:


try (
    ExecutorService executor =
            Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()
) {

    for (int i = 1; i <= 1000; i++) {

        int taskId = i;

        executor.submit(() -> {

            Thread.sleep(1000);

            return "Task " + taskId;
        });
    }
}


Concept:

Task 1 → Virtual Thread

Task 2 → Virtual Thread

Task 3 → Virtual Thread

...


Large number of blocking tasks handle karna practical ho sakta hai.


============================================================
55. PLATFORM THREAD VS VIRTUAL THREAD
============================================================

PLATFORM THREAD:

- OS thread se closely associated
- Relatively expensive resource
- Large numbers costly ho sakte hain


VIRTUAL THREAD:

- JVM managed
- Lightweight
- Large numbers of blocking tasks ke liye designed
- Java 21+


Use Case:

Platform Thread Pool:

Controlled number of worker threads


Virtual Threads:

Potentially one virtual thread per blocking task


============================================================
56. wait(), notify(), notifyAll()
============================================================

Ye low-level inter-thread communication methods hain.

Ye Object class ke methods hain.


wait():

Current thread specified object's monitor ko release karke wait karta hai.


notify():

Us monitor par wait kar rahe kisi ek thread ko wake-up eligibility deta hai.


notifyAll():

Us monitor par wait kar rahe sab threads ko wake-up eligibility deta hai.


IMPORTANT:

wait(), notify(), notifyAll()

ko synchronized context me same monitor ke saath use karna hota hai.


Example:

synchronized (lock) {

    lock.wait();
}


Another Thread:

synchronized (lock) {

    lock.notify();
}


Modern applications me higher-level concurrency utilities often preferred hoti hain.


============================================================
57. sleep() VS wait()
============================================================

sleep():

- Thread class method
- Current thread ko pause karta hai
- Held monitor lock automatically release nahi karta
- Time-based pause commonly used


wait():

- Object class method
- Inter-thread coordination ke liye
- Monitor lock release karta hai
- Synchronized context required


============================================================
58. SYNCHRONIZED VS LOCK
============================================================

synchronized:

Simple built-in locking mechanism.


Example:

synchronized (this) {

    // Critical Section
}


Lock API:

More advanced control provide kar sakti hai.


Example:

Lock lock =
        new ReentrantLock();


lock.lock();

try {

    // Critical Section

} finally {

    lock.unlock();
}


Benefits of explicit Lock APIs can include:

- tryLock()
- interruptible lock acquisition
- timed lock attempts
- multiple Condition objects


============================================================
59. ReentrantLock
============================================================

Example:

import java.util.concurrent.locks.Lock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock;


class Counter {

    private int count = 0;

    private final Lock lock =
            new ReentrantLock();


    public void increment() {

        lock.lock();

        try {

            count++;

        } finally {

            lock.unlock();
        }
    }
}


IMPORTANT:

unlock() ko finally block me rakhna chahiye.


============================================================
60. CONCURRENT COLLECTIONS
============================================================

Normal collections always thread-safe nahi hoti.


Example:

ArrayList

HashMap


Concurrent alternatives:

ConcurrentHashMap

CopyOnWriteArrayList

BlockingQueue


Example:

ConcurrentHashMap<Integer, String> map =
        new ConcurrentHashMap<>();


Useful when multiple threads shared collections access karte hain.


============================================================
61. BlockingQueue
============================================================

Producer-Consumer problems ke liye useful.


Example:

BlockingQueue<Integer> queue =
        new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(10);


Producer:

queue.put(100);


Consumer:

int value =
        queue.take();


Queue full:

put() wait kar sakta hai.


Queue empty:

take() wait kar sakta hai.


Low-level wait()/notify() ke comparison me often easier abstraction.


============================================================
62. DAEMON THREAD
============================================================

Daemon thread background supporting thread hota hai.


Example:

Thread t = new Thread(() -> {

    while (true) {

        System.out.println(
                "Background Work"
        );
    }
});


t.setDaemon(true);

t.start();


Important:

JVM generally exit kar sakti hai jab sirf daemon threads remaining hon.


Examples of background-style work:

- Monitoring
- Supporting services


============================================================
63. USER THREAD VS DAEMON THREAD
============================================================

USER THREAD:

Application ka normal important work.


DAEMON THREAD:

Background support work.


Example:

t.setDaemon(true);


Check:

t.isDaemon();


IMPORTANT:

setDaemon(true)

start() se pehle call karna hota hai.


============================================================
64. THREAD PRIORITY
============================================================

Priority range:

Thread.MIN_PRIORITY = 1

Thread.NORM_PRIORITY = 5

Thread.MAX_PRIORITY = 10


Example:

thread.setPriority(
        Thread.MAX_PRIORITY
);


IMPORTANT:

Priority sirf scheduler hint hai.

Execution order ki guarantee nahi hai.


============================================================
65. COMMON MULTITHREADING PROBLEMS
============================================================

1. Race Condition

Multiple threads shared data ko unsafe way me modify karte hain.


2. Deadlock

Threads ek dusre ke locks ka indefinitely wait karte hain.


3. Starvation

Kisi thread ko required CPU/resource/lock access repeatedly nahi milta.


4. Livelock

Threads active hote hain but useful progress nahi karte.


5. Visibility Problem

Ek thread ka update dusre thread ko timely/guaranteed visible nahi hota without proper synchronization.


============================================================
66. IMPORTANT INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
============================================================

Q1. Thread kya hai?

Thread process ke andar lightweight execution unit hai.


Q2. Process aur Thread me difference?

Process independent running program hai.

Thread process ke andar execution path hai.


Q3. start() aur run() me difference?

start() new thread start karta hai.

run() direct call karne par normal method ki tarah current thread me execute hota hai.


Q4. Thread create kaise karte hain?

Basic ways:

- Extend Thread
- Implement Runnable

Modern task execution:

- ExecutorService
- CompletableFuture
- Virtual Threads


Q5. Runnable better kyu ho sakta hai?

Task ko Thread object se separate karta hai aur class inheritance flexibility maintain karta hai.


Q6. sleep() kya karta hai?

Current thread ko specified time ke liye pause karta hai.


Q7. join() kya karta hai?

Current thread ko target thread ke completion ka wait karwata hai.


Q8. Race condition kya hai?

Jab result multiple threads ke unsafe timing/order par depend karta hai.


Q9. synchronized kya karta hai?

Critical section par mutual exclusion aur visibility guarantees provide karta hai.


Q10. volatile kya karta hai?

Shared variable ke updates ki visibility guarantee provide karta hai.


Q11. volatile count++ ko safe banata hai?

Nahi.

count++ atomic operation nahi hai.


Q12. Deadlock kya hai?

Jab threads cyclic lock/resource waiting ki wajah se progress nahi karte.


Q13. ExecutorService kya hai?

Tasks aur worker threads ko manage karne ka high-level concurrency framework.


Q14. Thread Pool kya hai?

Reusable managed worker threads ka pool.


Q15. Runnable aur Callable difference?

Runnable result return nahi karta.

Callable result return kar sakta hai aur checked exception throw kar sakta hai.


Q16. Future kya hai?

Asynchronous computation ke future result ko represent karta hai.


Q17. CompletableFuture kya hai?

Asynchronous task composition aur pipelines ke liye API.


Q18. Virtual Thread kya hai?

JVM-managed lightweight thread, especially large numbers of blocking tasks ke liye useful.


Q19. sleep() aur wait() difference?

sleep() monitor lock release nahi karta.

wait() monitor release karta hai aur coordination ke liye use hota hai.


Q20. synchronized method aur synchronized block?

Method poore method ke monitor-protected execution ko define karta hai.

Block sirf selected critical section ko protect karta hai.


